<exercises xml:id="exercises-sets">
<title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-sets-op-props"><p> <!-- \label{EXERCISE::sets::set.op.props} -->
	Prove each of the set operation rules in <xref ref="proposition-sets-rules-set-ops" />.
	Use the provided <xref ref="proof-proposition-sets-rules-set-ops" text="custom">proof</xref> <!-- TODO check this -->
	of the first of DeMorgan's Laws as a model for your proofs.
</p></exercise>

<exercisegroup xml:id="exercisegroup-sets-convert-to-symbols">
	<!-- TODO \refAdapt[s]{hunter+discrete}{2.2}{4 to 7} -->
	<title>Expressing relationships using the symbols of set theory</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
		In each of
		<xref ref="exercisegroup-sets-convert-to-symbols" text="type-local">Exercises</xref>,
		you are given a collection of sets (and possibly some elements of those sets),
		a collection of symbols,
		and a collection of statements about those sets and their elements.
		Use the given symbols to express the given statements in symbolic language.
		</p><p>
		Note that there may be more than one correct answer for each statement.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<exercise>
		<introduction><p>
			Sets:
			<md>
				<mrow> A \amp = \text{ the set of all Augustana students, } </mrow>
				<mrow> R \amp = \text{ the set of Augustana students who attend class regularly, } </mrow>
				<mrow> S \amp = \text{ the set of Augustana students who study diligently, } </mrow>
				<mrow> P \amp = \text{ the set of Augustana students who will pass all their courses. } </mrow>
			</md>
			Symbols:
			<me>
				A, \quad
				R, \quad
				S, \quad
				P, \quad
				\cmplmnt{R}, \quad
				\cmplmnt{S}, \quad
				\cmplmnt{P}, \quad
				\intersection, \quad
				\union, \quad
				=, \quad
				\ne, \quad
				\subseteq, \quad
				\subsetneqq, \quad
				\emptyset
			</me>.
		</p></introduction>
		<task><p> All Augustana students who attend class regularly and study diligently will pass all their courses. </p></task>
		<task><p> Some Augustana students attend class regularly but do not study diligently. </p></task>
		<task><p> Some Augustana students who study diligently will still fail a course. </p></task>
	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<introduction>

			<p>
			Recall that a square number is an integer which is equal to the square of some integer.
			(See the introduction preceding <xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-square-number-square-free-1" /> in <xref ref="exercises-proof-methods" />.)
			</p>

			<p>
			Sets:
			<md>
				<mrow> P \amp = \text{ the set of prime numbers, } </mrow>
				<mrow> E \amp = \text{ the set of even numbers, } </mrow>
				<mrow> S \amp = \text{ the set of square numbers. } </mrow>
			</md>
			Symbols:
			<me>
				2, \quad
				\N, \quad
				P, \quad
				E, \quad
				S, \quad
				\cmplmnt{\N}, \quad
				\cmplmnt{P}, \quad
				\cmplmnt{E}, \quad
				\cmplmnt{S}, \quad
				\in, \quad
				\intersection, \quad
				\union, \quad
				=, \quad
				\ne, \quad
				\subseteq, \quad
				\subsetneqq, \quad
				\emptyset, \quad
				\{\phantom{x}\}.
			</me>
			</p>

		</introduction>

		<task><p> <m>2</m> is the only even, prime number. </p></task>
		<task><p> There exist odd square numbers. </p></task>
		<task><p> No prime number is square. </p></task>
		<task><p> No square number is prime. </p></task>
		<task><p> It is not true that every natural number is either even or prime. </p></task>

	</exercise>

	<exercise>
		<introduction><p>
			Sets:
			<md>
				<mrow> \mathscr{F} \amp = \text{ the set of all functions in a single real variable, } </mrow>
				<mrow> \mathscr{C} \amp = \text{ the set of continuous functions, } </mrow>
				<mrow> \mathscr{D} \amp = \text{ the set of differentiable functions, } </mrow>
				<mrow> \mathscr{P} \amp = \text{ nonnegative functions } </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \setdef{f(x)}{ f(x) \ge 0 \text{ for all } x \text{ in the domain of } f }\text{.} </mrow>
			</md>
			Elements:
			<md><mrow>
				f_1(x) \amp = x^2 \amp
				f_2(x) \amp = \abs{x} \amp
				f_3(x) \amp = \tan x
			</mrow></md>
			Symbols:
			<me>
				\mathscr{F}, \;\;\;
				\mathscr{C}, \;\;\;
				\mathscr{D}, \;\;\;
				\mathscr{P}, \;\;\;
				\cmplmnt{\mathscr{F}}, \;\;\;
				\cmplmnt{\mathscr{C}}, \;\;\;
				\cmplmnt{\mathscr{D}}, \;\;\;
				\cmplmnt{\mathscr{P}}, \;\;\;
				f_1(x), \;\;\;
				f_2(x), \;\;\;
				f_3(x), \;\;\;
				\in, \;\;\;
				\intersection, \;\;\;
				\union, \;\;\;
				=, \;\;\;
				\ne, \;\;\;
				\subseteq, \;\;\;
				\subsetneqq, \;\;\;
				\emptyset.
			</me>
		</p></introduction>
		<task><p> The function <m>f_1(x)</m> is differentiable and nonnegative. </p></task>
		<task><p> The function <m>f_2(x)</m> is continuous and nonnegative, but not differentiable. </p></task>
		<task><p> The function <m>f_3(x)</m> is neither continuous nor nonnegative. </p></task>
		<task><p> Every differentiable function is continuous. </p></task>
		<task><p> Some continuous functions are not differentiable. </p></task>
		<task><p> Not every function is continuous. </p></task>
	</exercise>

</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup xml:id="exercisegroup-sets-investigate-set-ops">
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::sets::adv.set.ops} -->
	<title>Testing set equality</title>
	<introduction>
		For each of
		<xref ref="exercisegroup-sets-investigate-set-ops" text="type-local">Exercises</xref>,
		either formally prove the given equivalence of sets
		(using the <xref ref="test-sets-equality" text="custom">Test for Set Equality</xref>)
		or demonstrate that it is false by providing a <em>specific</em> counterexample.
	</introduction>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-sets-investigate-set-ops-disj-union"><p>
		<m>A = (A \relcmplmnt B) \disjunion (A \intersection B)</m>
	</p></exercise>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-sets-investigate-set-ops-double-relative-complement"><p>
		<m>A \relcmplmnt (A \relcmplmnt B) = B</m>
	</p></exercise>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-sets-investigate-set-ops-union-cart-prod"><p>
		<m>(A \cartprod B) \union (C \cartprod D) = (A \union C) \cartprod (B \union D)</m>
	</p></exercise>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-sets-investigate-set-ops-cart-prod-complement"><p>
		<m>A \cartprod (B \relcmplmnt C) = (A \cartprod B) \relcmplmnt (A \cartprod C)</m>
	</p></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-sets-words-disjoint-union-of-lengths"><p> <!-- \label{EXERCISE::sets::words.disjoint.union.of.lengths} -->
	Suppose <m>\Sigma</m> is an alphabet.
	Prove that <m>\words{\Sigma}</m> is the disjoint union of the subsets
	<me> \words{\Sigma}_0, \words{\Sigma}_1, \words{\Sigma}_2, \dotsc, \words{\Sigma}_n, \dotsc </me>.
</p></exercise>

<exercise>
	<p>
	Write out the elements of each of the sets
	<md><mrow>
		\amp \powset{ \emptyset }, \amp
		\amp \powset{ \, \powset{ \emptyset } \, }, \amp
		\amp \powset{ \, \powset{ \, \powset{ \emptyset } \, } \, }, \amp
		\amp \powset{ \, \powset{ \, \powset{ \, \powset{ \emptyset } \, } \, } \, }
	</mrow></md>.
	Make sure you have all the pairs of braces <m>\{\phantom{x}\}</m> you should have.
	</p><p>
	Without computing it, make a conjecture about the number of elements in the set
	<me> \powset{ \, \powset{ \, \powset{ \, \powset{ \, \powset{ \emptyset } \, } \, } \, } \, }. </me>
	</p>
</exercise>

<exercisegroup xml:id="exercisegroup-sets-investigate-pow-set-ops">
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::sets::adv.set.ops} -->
	<title>Properties of power sets</title>
	<introduction>
		For each of
		<xref ref="exercisegroup-sets-investigate-pow-set-ops" text="type-local">Exercises</xref>,
		either formally prove the given statement about power sets
		or demonstrate that it is false by providing a <em>specific</em> counterexample.
	</introduction>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-sets-investigate-pow-set-ops-union"><p>
		<m>\powset{A \union B} = \powset{A} \union \powset{B}</m>
	</p></exercise>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-sets-investigate-pow-set-ops-intersection"><p>
		<m>\powset{A \intersection B} = \powset{A} \intersection \powset{B}</m>
	</p></exercise>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-sets-investigate-pow-set-ops-subset"><p>
		If <m>A \subseteq B</m>, then  <m>\powset{A} \subseteq \powset{B}</m>.
	</p></exercise>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-sets-investigate-pow-set-ops-complement"><p>
		If <m>A \subseteq B</m>, then  <m>\powset{B \relcmplmnt A} = \powset{B} \relcmplmnt \powset{A}</m>.
	</p></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

</exercises>
